<h3>7. AI Crawler Accessibility</h3>
<p>If AI crawlers cannot access your content, your citability score is zero. Period.</p>
<p>ChatGPT uses GPTBot. Perplexity uses PerplexityBot. Google AI Overviews use Googlebot (the same crawler as traditional search). Each crawler must be allowed in your <code>robots.txt</code> file.</p>
<p>Server-side rendering (SSR) is also critical. Many AI crawlers struggle with JavaScript-heavy sites. Static HTML or SSR ensures your content is immediately accessible to every crawler.</p>
<p>Check our <a href="/blog/ai-crawlers-guide/">AI crawlers guide</a> to verify your site allows access from all major AI bots. And read our <a href="/blog/llms-txt-guide/">llms.txt guide</a> for the emerging standard that helps AI systems understand your site structure.</p>
<h3>8. Semantic Relevance and Topical Authority</h3>
<p>AI systems evaluate how well your content matches the semantic meaning of a query. Not just keywords. Meaning.</p>
<p>Research shows that content with cosine similarity scores above 0.88 to the target query achieves 7.3x higher citation rates compared to content with lower semantic alignment.</p>
<p>Building <a href="/blog/build-topical-authority/">topical authority</a> across an entire subject cluster increases the semantic relevance of every page in that cluster. A single blog post about "AI citability" scores lower than a site with 20+ articles covering AI search, GEO, structured data, E-E-A-T, and related topics.</p>
